                @*********Meal & Rest Break Periods Policy Section*********@
                <MudExpansionPanel>
                    <TitleContent>
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.h5">MEAL & REST BREAK PERIODS POLICY</MudText>
                    </TitleContent>
                    <ChildContent>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">MEAL BREAK PERIOD POLICY</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        An unpaid meal break period is normally scheduled near the midpoint of the work period.
                                        Each hourly employee is required by Company to take an unpaid meal period of one hour
                                        (1) duration for any workday longer than five (5) hours, with the meal period to
                                        commence (and the employee to punch out) no later than five (5) hours after the
                                        commencement of the employee’s work shift. Employees must punch out the timecard
                                        before and after the meal break.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Employees whose daily work schedule will be completed in six hours or less may, upon
                                        agreement with Company, waive the daily meal period. Each employee who works more
                                        than ten hours in one day is required by Company to take, during that workday, a second
                                        unpaid meal period of not less than one (1) hour, except that an employee whose work
                                        during that workday will be completed in 12 hours or less, and who took a first meal
                                        period commencing at or prior to working five (5) hours during that workday, may waive
                                        the second meal period.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Employees are relieved and released of all duties during the meal period. If any manager
                                        or Company representative encourages Employee to work during their meal period
                                        without pay, Employee is to report such conduct immediately to Management. Any
                                        employee who takes less than the required meal break(s) or fails to punch out and punch
                                        in for the required meal periods, or does both, repeatedly during any pay period, will be
                                        subject to discipline, up to and including termination.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">REST BREAK PERIODS POLICY</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        A paid rest break period, consisting of a minimum of ten (10) minutes, is normally
                                        scheduled near the midpoint of each half of a full workday. Non-exempt employees are
                                        required by law and Company policy to take a paid rest break, consisting of a minimum
                                        of ten (10) minutes, during every four (4) hours worked or major fraction thereof. If, for
                                        example, employee works 6.5 hours, Employee is entitled to 20 minutes of break time, 10
                                        minutes for the initial 4 hours worked and another 10 minutes for the major fraction of
                                        the remaining 4 hours, i.e., 2.5 hours. Further, if you are scheduled to work two (2) or
                                        more hours overtime in one workday, you are required by law and Company policy to
                                        take an additional paid rest break, consisting of a minimum of ten (10) minutes, at the end
                                        of the first eight (8) hours of the workday.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Violations of this Break Period policy will be subject to discipline, up to and including
                                        termination.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">LACTATION ACCOMMODATION (LABOR CODE SECTION 1030)</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        In compliance with Labor Code Section 1030, Company will provide a reasonable
                                        amount of break time to accommodate an employee desiring to express breast milk for
                                        the employee’s infant child. The break time shall, if possible, be taken concurrently with
                                        other break periods already provided. Non-exempt employees should clock out for any
                                        time taken that does not run concurrently with normally scheduled rest periods, and such
                                        time will be unpaid unless otherwise required by federal or state law. Company will also
                                        make a reasonable effort to provide the employee with the use of a room or other location
                                        in close proximity to the employee’s work area, for the employee to express milk in
                                        private.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        Employees should notify their supervisor or the Human Resources to request time and
                                        make other necessary arrangements to express breast milk under this policy.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        No provision of this policy applies or is enforced if it conflicts with or is superseded by
                                        any requirement or prohibition contained in a state or local law or regulation. Anyone
                                        with knowledge of such a conflict or potential conflict should contact the Human
                                        Resources.
                                    </p>
                                </MudText>
                            </ChildContent>
                        </MudExpansionPanel>
                    </ChildContent>
                </MudExpansionPanel>

                @*********Code of Conduct Section*********@
                <MudExpansionPanel>
                    <TitleContent>
                        <MudText Typo="Typo.h5">CODE OF CONDUCT</MudText>
                    </TitleContent>
                    <ChildContent>
                        <MudExpansionPanel>
                            <TitleContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.h6">INTRODUCTION</MudText>
                            </TitleContent>
                            <ChildContent>
                                <MudText Typo="Typo.body2">
                                    <p>
                                        Company expects each employee to conduct himself/herself in a professional and ethical
                                        manner. This means that, among other things, employees are expected to conduct
                                        themselves in a manner that will uphold the Company’s reputation for excellent customer
                                        service, courteousness, efficiency, safety and timeliness.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        While Company reserves the right to dismiss employees at any time, it also may take
                                        other disciplinary measures against employees who violate work rules or fail to
                                        satisfactorily perform their job duties. Examples of disciplinary action include a warning
                                        letter, suspension without pay, demotion, or discharge.
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        In an effort to alert employees to expectations of them and to apprise them of their
                                        obligations and responsibilities regarding their conduct, listed below are examples of
                                        types of behavior that may result in disciplinary action. The first list is a list of offenses
                                        that typically will be more serious and even result in immediate dismissal. The second list
                                        is a list of offenses that are not as grave but are still likely to result in disciplinary action.
                                        Of course, Company reserves the right to determine appropriate disciplinary action based
                                        on the individual circumstances in its sole discretion. Because we cannot anticipate every
                                        situation that might arise, these lists merely provide examples of problematic conduct.
                                        Company expects employees to always behave lawfully, ethically, and with good sense.
                                    </p>
                                    <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Style="display:list-item">
                                        <u><b>Actions Which May Result in Immediate Discharge</b></u>
                                        <ol>
                                            <li>
                                                Dishonest conduct, including, but not limited to, unauthorized taking or
                                                possession of Company’s property, unauthorized possession or taking of a fellow
                                                employee’s property, taking bribes, or unauthorized charges against Company’s
                                                account.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Any unauthorized possession, use, purchase, sale, transfer, or being under the
                                                influence of an illegal drug, alcohol, or cannabis products on Company premises.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Working for a competitor or engaging in any activity that poses a conflict with the
                                                Company's interests or appears to do so.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Taking money, merchandises or services from a customer or vendor for personal
                                                gain without authorization.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Improperly disclosing or using trade secrets, proprietary, or confidential
                                                information about Company, its partners, its employees, or its agents.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>
                                                Insubordination, derogatory or defamatory behavior toward management
                                                personnel, other employees, Company, or its partners.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>Sexual or other harassment.</li>
                                            <li>
                                                False statements, misrepresentations, or omissions on documents or records, such
                                                as resumes, job applications, or timecards.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>Failing to return to work after an authorized leave of absence.</li>
                                            <li>
                                                Possession of firearms or other weapons on Company premises or while
                                                performing Company business without authorization.
                                            </li>
                                            <li>Violent conduct or threat of violence.</li>
                                            <li>Felony conviction or pleading of no contest.</li>
                                            <li>Gambling on Company premises.</li>
                                            <li>Serious misconduct of any kind.</li>
                                        </ol>
                                    </MudText>

